{"key":"post-8645405","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8645405</id>\n<content>Grains should never be added to boiling water.&amp;nbsp; That's a major cause of burst kernels.&amp;nbsp; At the very least, add the grains to cold water and then bring to a boil.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Hot water hydrates the grains much faster, so if you dump dry grains into boiling water, how can they absorb that much water without bursting?&amp;nbsp; The soak allows them to slowly absorb water, eliminating that problem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some growers are satisfied with ten percent burst kernels.&amp;nbsp; Personally, if I saw ten TOTAL burst kernels, I'd toss the whole batch and start over. Loose starch in jars is never a good thing.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8645478</next>\n<prev>8645140</prev>\n<first>8597867</first>\n<last>8648206</last>\n<when>1216276377</when>\n<utime>07/17/08 09:32 AM</utime>\n</post>"}